1 WHEREAS, twenty-eight Mississippi River Basin state fishery agencies, the United
2 States Fish and Wildlife Service, the Bureau of Reclamation, the United States Geological
3 Survey, the Tennessee Valley Authority, the Chippewa-Cree Tribe, and the Chickasaw
4 Nation ratified the Mississippi Interstate Cooperative Resource Agreement in 1990 and
5 formed the Mississippi Interstate Cooperative Resource Association (MICRA) in 1991 to
6 improve the management of interjurisdictional fishery resources in the basin; and
7 WHEREAS, recognizing the economic, ecologic, and cultural value of the diverse
8 interjurisdictional fishery resources in the Mississippi River Basin and the complexity and
9 severity of issues facing resource management agencies, Congress has acknowledged the
10 need for the establishment of a Mississippi River Basin Fishery Commission for basin-wide,
11 interagency collaboration in the establishment of shared management objectives, and the
12 collaborative planning, implementation, and evaluation of management actions to provide
13 for the long-term biologic and economic sustainability of interjurisdictional fishery resources
14 in the basin; and
15 WHEREAS, with long-term sustainability of interjurisdictional fishery resources
16 depending on the control of aquatic invasive species within the Mississippi River Basin, the
17 commission is vital to provide for coordinated, inter-agency, basin-wide management,
18 control, and removal of invasive carps and other prioritized aquatic invasive species within
19 the basin; and
20 WHEREAS, by consent of Congress, and as directed by federal law under the
21 Magnuson-Stevens Fishery Conservation and Management Act, 16 U.S.C. 1801 et seq., and
22 the Interjurisdictional Fisheries Act of 1986, 16 U.S.C. 4101 et seq., sustainable fisheries
23 within the United States coastal waters of the Pacific and Atlantic Oceans, the Caribbean
24 Sea, and the Gulf of America, have been managed by multi-state commissions and fishery
25 councils for many decades; and
26 WHEREAS, the interjurisdictional and international fishery resources of the Great
27 Lakes are cooperatively managed by the Great Lakes Fishery Commission, operating
28 through the 1954 Convention on Great Lake Fisheries; and
29 WHEREAS, the Mississippi River Basin Fishery Commission will improve the
30 management and utilization of sustainable interjurisdictional fishery resources in the
